fields.description: This project involves the application of nonequilibrium molecular dynamics (NEMD) computer simulations to study the atomistic flow properties of complex fluids, particularly polymer melts of variout molecular architectures. The systems studied will vary from linear, hyperbranched and dendrimer chain molecules with varying degrees of molecular mass and polydispersity. The systems studied will be under shear, elongational and mixed shear + elongational flow. The simulations are computationally very intensive and will make significant use of the CPU time available. Our overall goal is to understand the macroscopic flow behaviour of such complex fluids by analysing their microscopic response to the applied flow fields.

fields.description:
We propose to use gSTAR to search for an exotic type of star known as a pulsar.

A pulsar is the compact remnant of a supernova explosion, produced when a normal star collapses under its own weight. Pulsars have powerful magnetic fields that produce beams of radio emission from their north and south poles. As the pulsar rotates, these beams sweep across the Galaxy to be detected at Earth as a periodic sequence of radio pulses. Some pulsars are found in orbit with a companion star; these "binary systems" enable very precise tests of our understanding of gravity. The most interesting binary systems are difficult to discover because the pulsar signal is distorted by orbital motion.

We require the computational power of gSTAR to correct this distortion and improve our chances of finding the most extreme binary systems, such as a pulsar in orbit around a black hole.
fields.name: Accelerated Pulsar Survey

fields.description: The DRAGONS project will simulate formation of the first galaxies and the co-evolution of the inter-galactic medium during the epoch of reionization using an integrated suite of state-of-the-art hydro-dynamic, N-body and semi-analytic models of galaxy formation. The origin of the first galaxies represents a fundamental unanswered question motivating a raft of new international telescopes, including the Square Kilometer Array and James Webb Space Telescope. DRAGONS will answer a range of questions including how and when the first galaxies formed, what they looked like, and how massive they were. With 4 postdoctoral researchers and 4 PhD students already committed to the research for the next 5 years, DRAGONS will provide a legacy of new expertise in first galaxies science, a topic that will dominate cosmology in the coming decade.
fields.name: DRAGONS on GPUs

This is important for electron transport through interfaces in solar cells and photo-catalysis, for development of efficient solar cells to address society's ever increasing energy needs, as well as for powering nano-machines, and optical manipulation of dielectric/organic nano-particles.

The 3D-FDTD method, in which the investigator has wide experience, will be applied on plasmonic nano-structures illuminated by a light beam, causing nano-focusing for field enhancement, and generating force/torque on the structure itself or on nano-particles in fluid suspension.

FDTD Lumerical software (of which installation is requested) will be used to efficiently calculate the 3D EM-field, and Lorentz force calculation is implemented to model the movement of nano-particles in the viscous environment.

fields.description: A main aim of this project is to improve the 3D linear MHD helioseismic wave propagation code SPARC (Seismic Propagation Through Active Regions and Convection) to more realistically treat the atmosphere overlying solar active regions, where currently simplistic approximations are made. This is mainly due to severe time­step constraints associated with an exponentially increasing Alfven wave speed above the solar surface. More specifically, we wanted to understand impact of the Alfven wave­speed limiter that is commonly applied by various MHD codes (including our own) on the fast-Alfven mode conversion process, which recent studies have shown to have the potential to modify the seismic wave-path through the solar atmosphere. We will use SPARC to simulate artificial helioseismology data sets, and with the aid of local helioseismic diagnostic tools (such as time-distance helioseismology and helioseismic holography) we will attempt to quantify the effects of fast-Alfven mode conversion on the wave travel times.
fields.name: Modelling Fast-Alfven Mode Conversion in the Sun

fields.description: This project focuses on semantic, sentiment and statistical analysis of mobile app user reviews. The current dataset consists of approximately 8.7 million reviews from 5.25 million users over 17.3 thousand apps. To perform a detailled vocabulary analysis, we need to normalise and sanitise the dataset, consisting of a number of processing steps. In particular spell correction involves computation of string distance and substring manipulation on approximately 203 million words, individually. Hence the need for the multiple cores and high computation power. Once spell correction is completed, context sensitivity of terms used in user reviews needs to be applied via unigrams, increasing complexity exponentially etc.
fields.name: Analysis of Mobile App Reviews

fields.description:
We will use gstar for 3 main projects:

- a study of magnetised, supersonic turbulence in molecular clouds
- studies of the magnetorotational instability in accretion discs
- studies of star cluster formation from magnetised clouds

 The first project is mainly a comparison between different codes on the basic statistical properties of magnetised turbulence at high Mach number. The second will be the first time that global discs have been simulated with magnetic fields with the Smoothed Particle Magnetohydrodynamics method. This will open the door to understanding the operation of the Magneto-rotational instability in warped, bent and binary accretion discs. Finally, we will use gstar for our ongoing studies of star formation from magnetised turbulent clouds.
fields.name: Magnetic fields in star formation

fields.description:
Using an updated version of widely used MURaM code [1] designed for simulations of solar magneto-convection, I plan to produce a grid of well-resolved photospheric radiative magneto-convection models on a range of magnetic activity levels with externally induced, as well as self-produced by local photospheric dynamo magnetic fields. The MURaM code has been updated to include a newer version of the equation of state which allows now to simulate higher layers of the solar atmosphere and deeper layers of the solar convection zone with better precision. Produced models will be used in a wide range of applications, which include local helioseismology, studies of origins of solar and stellar magnetic fields, dynamics of solar chromosphere, in understanding the effects of magnetic fields on determining solar and stellar abundances, and ultimately will lead to a better understanding of solar and stellar activity, structure and evolution.
[1] Vögler, A., Shelyag, S., et al. A&A, 2005, 429, 335 (249 citations)

fields.description: The common envelope interaction happens between an evolving, expanding star and any nearby companion. This interaction gives rise to scores of compact binaries and mergers, including type Ia supernova progenitors. Surprisingly, it was recently found that planets might survive the common envelope interaction with their parent star and thus can change the course of the star's life. We have adapted and tested a grid code, Enzo, to simulate common envelope interactions. We would like to use gStar computing time to (i) simulate the interaction between a red giant star and sub-stellar companions with the aim of understanding how stars react to swallowing planets (work supported by ARCDP grant), (ii) predict light curves of common envelope interactions by pairing the hydrodynamical simulations with a "light module", and use them to explain observations of current and upcoming surveys (work supported by an ARC Future Fellowship to De Marco).

This data is primarily in the form of optical and infrared observational data from various international telescope facilities, but includes other materials, such as documents and executable routines.

Analysis of complex integral-field data is computationally expensive, especially in the era of large surveys. This project will begin with analysis of data from the Atlas3D Survey of 260 nearby galaxies, in particular to deriving star-formation histories by spectral fitting. This work will eventually develop to include effort on the MaNGA Survey - an extension of the Sloan Digital Sky Survey - and SAMI - a new multi-integral field spectrograph at the AAT. These projects require large storage, and access to multiple CPUs with sizeable amounts of memory. The gSTAR facility, using 'general access', is perfectly suited to this purpose.

The aim of this project is to model the superfluid interior of a neutron star. The goal is to understand how superfluidity can affect phenomena such as radio pulsar glitches and how it can affect gravitational wave emission mechanisms.
In order to make progress we will attack the problem from several angles, making use of quantum dynamical simulations of vortex motion (2D and 3D), 1D long term hydrodynamical evolutions of the rotation rate of the star and shorter full 3D evolutions to study modes and instabilities of the superfluid.

fields.description: This research aims to determine the ionization structures of a carefully vetted sample of planetary nebulae. Our goal is to derive physical conditions and chemical abundances of these planetary nebulae and obtain the central star characteristics. We aim to determine stellar evolutionary stage through photo-ionization modelling. The latest photo-ionization codes allow us to model a gaseous nebula, yielding the nebular size at the current epoch, and the stellar parameters that can be used to accurately trace the stellar evolutionary stages of the central star. The results will shed light on the formation and evolution of planetary nebulae.

["The MuRAM MHD code we use is the non-ideal MHD equations solver on a uniform cartesian grid. The code uses 4-th order central difference scheme for spatial derivatives, 4-th order Runge-Kutta scheme to advance the solution in time, and domain decomposition scheme for MPI-parallel processing. The code also uses short-characteristics radiative solver to account for radiative energy exchange. The solution is stabilised against numerical instabilities using artificial diffusivity source terms. Full description of the methods may be found in V\u00f6gler, Shelyag et al. (2005).\r\nPostprocessing of the simulated solar models is also planned. It includes calculation of detailed radiative transport in one dimension (three-dimensional radiative transport is planned for future). The codes SPINOR (Shelyag et al., 2007), RH (Uitenbroek, 2010) and NICOLE are MPI-parallel codes with parallelisation efficiency close to 100% for 1-D radiative transport calculations, since the radiation rays are independent in 1-D computations and can be treated as separate, non-communicating processes.\r\nThe codes are written in C/C++ and Fortran, thus no specialised software is used except for Interactive Data Language (IDL), which is used for simulation control. Three-dimensional visualisation (see provided figure) is carried out locally using VAPOR 3D visualisation package (Clyne, J., Mininni, P., Norton, A., and Rast, M. \"Interactive desktop analysis of high resolution simulations: application to turbulent plume dynamics and current sheet formation\", New Journal of Physics 9 (2007) 301.)"]

["SPARC is a 3D linearised MHD solver which makes use of advanced numerical methods in the computation of spatial derivatives and to evolve the system forward in time. This is necessary in order that the computation be accurate and efficient. To capture variations in the vertical direction, a sixth order, low dissipation and dispersion compact finite differences method with fifth\u00ad order accurate boundary conditions is applied. A Fourier spectral method is applied in the horizontal directions in order to compute the derivatives along these directions.  The solution is temporally evolved using a second\u00adorder optimized Runge\u00adKutta integrator  The horizontal boundaries are chosen to be periodic while the vertical boundaries are required to be absorbent (PMLs).\r\nEach variable is an array of dimensions (nx,ny,nz), where the three components are the number of grid points in directions (x, y, z) respectively. The sizes of the problems of study are rather large, requiring distributed computing. The algorithm involves dividing the arrays into chunks among processors as equitably as possible. Denoting the number of processors by nP , the storage pattern is determined such that each processor contains approximately (nx,[ny/nP],nz) sized chunks of the original array. Thus the parallelism is only in one direction; this makes the book\u00adkeeping much easier when exchanging information between processors. The parallelism is concordant with the Message Passing Interface (MPI) standards v1.2 and OpenMPI. SPARC also utilises the fftw and cfitsio modules.  "]

["We have encountered two main issues with the gSTAR system and batch queue:

1. The “invalid device index” error.

There is incompatibility between the GPU device indices returned by cudaGetDeviceCount (and relative functions) and what is allocated by the scheduler in the $PBS_GPUFILE environment variable. The scheduler correctly returns the index of a device within a node with many GPUs, while the cuda function sees only the devices for which the user is the owner. Because the gSTAR queue-setup is changing the ownership of the devices according to the user they have been allocated to, the returned indices from the cuda function do not match the true ones returned by the scheduler.

2. The max-job limit

Originally, there was a 32 maximum job limit for each user, regardless of the resources that the jobs were using. This was barely enough for us to actually use all of our allocated time in Q3 and Q4 2012, assuming that all went well with gSTAR nodes and queue (see the previous problem). Once this issue had been identified, and the limit increased to 64 jobs, we are able to access sufficient nodes to take full advantage of allocated time."]

["The software used if the Lumerical FDTD software package by FDTD Solutions, it is enabled for parallel computations via MPI. It has been successfully used on a number of cores variable between 16 and 256, with further postprocessing and numerical feedback via MATLAB scripts.

The FDTD modeling is carried out on a closed domain where the particle is illuminated by a plane wave  or Gaussian source. Perfectly matched layers (PMLs) are used on the z-axis boundaries, while periodic boundaries conditions are placed on the x- and y-axes when a plane wave source of infinite extent is required. This is necessary to avoid diffraction of the plane wave source at the domain edge, but postulates a periodicity of the structure. This is addressed by enlarging the domain to a wide enough size to distance the periodicized particles and avoid coupling. This increases the time and memory requirements for the model, combined with the requirement to reduce the effect of staircase approximation, which is addressed by reducing the square mesh size around the particle to values smaller than 1 nm (or about wavelength=1000).

For the cross-sections calculations, the disk is illuminated by a total-field scattered-field (TFSF) source, which decomposes the total fields in incident fields (known) and scattered fields (unknown), where FDTD remains valid because of Maxwells equations linearity. The region inside the TFSF is solved for the total fields, while the one outside for the scattered fields. The regions are separated by a virtual surface generating the incident wave. If all the structures remain inside the TFSF, there is no incident wave outside, and scattering can be separately assessed. From the known incident power, the absorbed power is calculated. The domain boundary is made of PMLs to avoid scattered field reflection.

We introduced a general model for calculating forces and torques which takes into account the peculiarities of the 3D finite difference time domain (FDTD) method, in particular using the Lumerical software package to calculate the Lorentz force. In order to accommodate the finest possible mesh an optimization was made by using periodic boundary conditions. Fine meshing <1 nm size was implemented to reveal small spatial fluctuations of the calculated fields. The materials were modeled according to the multi-coefficient polynomial approximation of the refractive index values tabulated in the Lumerical database. We separated the contribution to the radiation pressure of the electrical charge density from that of the current density; in a dielectric they are only due to the “bound” electrons, while in a metal there is a contribution from the “free” electrons as well, and they are accounted for by the conductivity contribution to the imaginary part of the metal permittivity. In the present FDTD formulation, only the free electrons contributed to the divergence of D. The calculation of charge density through the divergence of the electric field had to take into account an unavoidable feature of the FDTD method in that each field component is calculated in a different point of the Yee cell. This is compounded with the fact that, while the component of the electric field parallel to the metal interface is continuous, the perpendicular component is discontinuous and, while for at interfaces this is straightforward, on curved surfaces the staircase effect given by the FDTD mesh makes the operation ambiguous. A special interpolation procedure had to be devised and published to overcome this issue.

The E- and H-fields were also exported into files for further processing by MATLAB, to calculate power absorbed, feeding into structural deformation calculations (the forces are calculated and the shape and position of the calculated structure after a defined time interval are modified in the layout, repeating the simulation), heat transfer calculation via Fourier approach, and charge motion calculation via population rate equations in semiconductors, feeding back in optical simulation via refractive index variation calculation (Drude model).

A 3D model of 9.6 solar mass star of zero metallicity was evolved to around 250ms after bounce. The explosion is well underway by then, with a shock radius of around 3000km at the end of the simulation.

Due to some throughput problems on swinStar (long queueing times), we decided to evolve this model mostly on the raijin system at the NCI National Facility. Finding that throughput was better for moderately large applications (64-128 cores), we decided to conduct some long-time 2D simulations (covering several seconds after bounce) of supernova explosions of stars around 11 solar masses to make more efficient use of swinStar. Explosions in this mass range have been suggested as an explanation for underluminous supernovae with energies of only a few 10^50 ergs. However, multi-D simulations have not yet been able to predict saturated explosion energies in this mass range yet. Our new neutrino transport algorithm allows us to simulate long enough to determine saturation values for the explosion energy."]

["A 9.6 solar mass progenitor was evolved well into the explosion phase in 3D. Immediately after the onset of the explosion, we observe a vigorous growth of Rayleigh-Taylor instabilities that lead to the fast ejection of relatively neutron-rich material from the vicinity of the young neutron star. The neutron-rich character of the Rayleigh-Taylor plumes is a strong indicator that the \"weak r-process\" with the production of heavy elements up to silver and palladium (as suggested in the proposal) may be viable. A detailed comparative analysis of the ejecta composition between 2D and 3D will be carried out within the next months. The attached file shows the matter entropy in an equatorial slice through the 3D model at the end of the simulation. Both the development of Rayleigh-Taylor plumes in the outer ejecta behind the shock as well as a global asymmetry in the neutrino-driven wind following at later times.\r\n\r\nThe additional 2D long-time simulations of stars between 11 and 12 solar masses follow (for the first time in multi-group neutrino transport models) the propagation of the shock out into the helium shell of the progenitor. They show that explosion energies of 1...2*10^50 ergs can be reached even in supposedly marginal 2D simulations. While previous 2D models of neutrino-driven explosions were often criticised for not showing that the envelope can actually be unbound, our long-time simulations demonstrate that the explosion are sufficiently energetic to achieve the expulsion of the envelope. Furthermore, we obtain neutron star masses and pulsar kicks that are roughly compatible with typically observed values. Thus, our numerical models underpin the hypothesis that intermediate mass stars slightly above 10 solar masses are the origin of type IIp supernovae of moderate explosion energy. "]

["Our simulations make use of a general relativistic finite-volume based solver for the equations of hydrodynamics [1,2] formulated in spherical polar coordinates. Time step constraints due to the convergence of cells near the axis are alleviated by a mesh coarsening scheme [3]. The hydro module is parallelized using domain decomposition in the angular coordinates (,). It dominates the total computer time requirements.
The equations for the space-time metric are solved in the conformal flatness approximation, which involves the solution of non-linear Poisson equations (presently solved in the monopole approximation using a fixed-point iteration scheme). Source terms due to neutrino interactions are computed by approximately solving the stationary neutrino transport equation along radial rays with an approximate flux factor, similar to the grey scheme of [4]. This involves the radial integration of four ODEs for each of the neutrino energy groups (typically 21) in each time-step.

Software packages used in the code include: LAPACK (solution of linear systems) and HDF5 (parallel I/O). The code is written in FORTRAN 90, but also includes some auxiliary routines in C.

["The software used if the Lumerical FDTD software package by FDTD Solutions, it is enabled for parallel computations via MPI. It has been successfully used on a number of cores variable between 16 and 256, with further postprocessing and numerical feedback via MATLAB scripts.

The FDTD modeling is carried out on a closed domain where the particle is illuminated by a plane wave or Gaussian source. Perfectly matched layers (PMLs) are used on the z-axis boundaries, while periodic boundaries conditions are placed on the x- and y-axes when a plane wave source of infinite extent is required. This is necessary to avoid diffraction of the plane wave source at the domain edge, but postulates a periodicity of the structure. This is addressed by enlarging the domain to a wide enough size to distance the periodicized particles and avoid coupling. This increases the time and memory requirements for the model, combined with the requirement to reduce the effect of staircase approximation, which is addressed by reducing the square mesh size around the particle to values smaller than 1 nm (or about wavelength=1000).

For the cross-sections calculations, the disk is illuminated by a total-field scattered-field (TFSF) source, which decomposes the total fields in incident fields (known) and scattered fields (unknown), where FDTD remains valid because of Maxwells equations linearity. The region inside the TFSF is solved for the total fields, while the one outside for the scattered fields. The regions are separated by a virtual surface generating the incident wave. If all the structures remain inside the TFSF, there is no incident wave outside, and scattering can be separately assessed. From the known incident power, the absorbed power is calculated. The domain boundary is made of PMLs to avoid scattered field reflection.

We introduced a general model for calculating forces and torques which takes into account the peculiarities of the 3D finite difference time domain (FDTD) method, in particular using the Lumerical software package to calculate the Lorentz force. In order to accommodate the finest possible mesh an optimization was made by using periodic boundary conditions. Fine meshing <1 nm size was implemented to reveal small spatial fluctuations of the calculated fields. The materials were modeled according to the multi-coefficient polynomial approximation of the refractive index values tabulated in the Lumerical database. We separated the contribution to the radiation pressure of the electrical charge density from that of the current density; in a dielectric they are only due to the “bound” electrons, while in a metal there is a contribution from the “free” electrons as well, and they are accounted for by the conductivity contribution to the imaginary part of the metal permittivity. In the present FDTD formulation, only the free electrons contributed to the divergence of D. The calculation of charge density through the divergence of the electric field had to take into account an unavoidable feature of the FDTD method in that each field component is calculated in a different point of the Yee cell. This is compounded with the fact that, while the component of the electric field parallel to the metal interface is continuous, the perpendicular component is discontinuous and, while for at interfaces this is straightforward, on curved surfaces the staircase effect given by the FDTD mesh makes the operation ambiguous. A special interpolation procedure had to be devised and published to overcome this issue.

The E- and H-fields were also exported into files for further processing by MATLAB, to calculate power absorbed, feeding into structural deformation calculations (the forces are calculated and the shape and position of the calculated structure after a defined time interval are modified in the layout, repeating the simulation), heat transfer calculation via Fourier approach, and charge motion calculation via population rate equations in semiconductors, feeding back in optical simulation via refractive index variation calculation (Drude model).
"]
